article.headline: Charlotte 67, Detroit 61
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- A game against the Detroit Shock could
not have come at a better time for the Charlotte Sting.

In desperate need of a win, the Sting snapped their three-game
losing streak Thursday with a 67-61 victory over Detroit. It gave
Charlotte a 4-0 season sweep over the Eastern Conference leading
Shock.

"For some reason, when we play Detroit, we really focus and
execute our game plan," said Charlotte coach Trudi Lacey.
"Detroit is a tremendous team, but this game was more about us
because we had not been playing very well lately."

That changed against the Shock, which had its four-game winning
streak snapped.

Detroit, which now has a two-game lead over the Sting for the
conference lead, was held to a season-low 22 points in the first
half.

"We did our normal thing when we play them -- we panic," said
Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer. "It was painful to watch us play.
Fortunately, we don't play them again until the playoffs. That is
the only positive we can take."

Of Detroit's six losses this season, four have come against
Charlotte.

Allison Feaster scored 18 points to lead Charlotte and Andrea
Stinson added 14. It was the best game the two Charlotte stars have
played since before the All-Star break.

The Sting came out of the break flat and that contributed to
their losing streak.

"We weren't playing very well since the All-Star break and we
needed to get back on track," Feaster said. "So this win was
huge."

Ruth Riley scored 16 points to lead Detroit, which is admittedly
baffled by Charlotte this season.

"It's a frustrating loss because this is an Eastern Conference
team we haven't beaten yet," Riley said. "Next time, we'll have
to play smarter basketball."

The Sting built a 27-12 lead in the first half and didn't let
up.

After Stinson tied it at 10 with a jumper, the Sting went on a
19-2 run to put Detroit on its heels. Charlotte went into halftime
with a 35-22 advantage.

But Detroit came out with more intensity in the second half,
gradually chipping into Charlotte's lead until the Shock cut it to
55-54 on Swin Cash's driving layup.

The Sting took a timeout, then responded by upping the tempo to
wear out Detroit. Stinson scored on a 15-footer, Teana McKiver
blocked Cash's shot, and Tammy Sutton-Brown pushed Charlotte's lead
to 59-54 with a short jumper.

After Detroit turned it over on a bad pass from Deanna Nolan,
Brown (10 points) sealed the game for Charlotte with a layup.

Elaine Powell scored 14 for Detroit, and Cash added 10.
